AGI - US President, Joe Biden, signed the aid package that provides military assistance to Ukraine after months of negotiations and debates. The measure, approved by the Senate last night and the total value of 95 billion dollars, includes almost 61 billion dollars in aid to Ukraine, 26 billion dollars for Israel and 8 billion dollars for the Indo-Pacific.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Biden signed the legislation authorizing military aid, crucial to the defense of Ukraine from the Russian offensive, stating that Washington will begin sending the first tranche to Kiev within a few hours. "I have just converted into law the National Security Package approved by the House of Representatives this weekend, and yesterday by the Senate," he said, adding that he will ensure "that shipments begin immediately, in the next few hours". The American President urged Israel to allow Palestinians access to humanitarian aid "without delay". &nbsp;&nbsp;
<h2> Long-range missiles sent secretly
National Security Counselor Jake Sullivan revealed that the US president secretly sent ATACMS long-range missiles to Ukraine in March. Sullivan added that the United States "will send more".&nbsp; The news, which was already leaked on the media, was confirmed in a press conference at the White House. Sullivan explained that Biden ordered his men in February to provide Ukraine "a significant number" of ATACMS missiles, but only because they were used "in Ukrainian territory" and not against Russia. A month later, in March, those missiles were delivered to Ukraine, Sullivan revealed.
&nbsp;
Although the news had not been made public at the time, these missiles were included in a military aid package worth 300 million dollars (about 280 million euros) that Biden approved on March 12, still explained the president's advisor. Biden decided to approve the expedition after the U.S. intelligence had concluded that Russia had used long-range missiles from other countries, particularly from North Korea, on the battlefield and in the face of increasing Russian attacks against Ukrainian civil infrastructure. Sullivan has avoided specifying the exact number of missiles sent to Ukrainian forces, although he has assured that others will be sent, especially now that Congress has approved a package of foreign aid that includes 61 billion dollars (about 57 billion euros) of military assistance in Kiev.
&nbsp;
The debate on sending ATACMS missiles in Ukraine has been going on for months within the Biden administration, where some feared to provoke an escalation of war with Moscow and that Ukraine would use them to attack targets within Russia. During the press conference, Sullivan was asked if there is still fear that Ukraine attacks Russia with ATACMS missiles, but he replied that the executive received guarantees from the Ukrainians that these weapons will be used only in their territory. "The Ukrainian government has assured us that they will not use them outside the borders of Ukraine," said Sullivan. And he recalled that the Ukrainian executive also made these commitments in the past, for example with the HIMARS rockets, whose range is about 50 miles (about 80 kilometers), committing to use these American weapons directly against Russia. The first time Biden mentioned the possibility of sending ATACMS missiles to Ukraine was in July last year, during the NATO summit in Vilnius (Lituania), but at that time the United States had decided to prioritize the sending of artillery in Ukraine, which was what was most used on the battlefield.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

